WEBVTT

00:07.382 --> 00:09.592
- Previously
on "Resident Alien"...

00:09.635 --> 00:11.725
- You are the Greys.
What are you going to do?

00:11.762 --> 00:14.262
- We will destroy you
and everyone you care about.

00:14.306 --> 00:15.886
- There’s alien activity here.

00:15.933 --> 00:17.483
I know it.
- What are you gonna do?

00:17.518 --> 00:19.888
- Call the Alien Tracker and
tell him to come to Patience

00:19.937 --> 00:21.307
and find himself an alien.

00:21.355 --> 00:23.775
- I need a refill
on these pain meds.

00:23.815 --> 00:25.645
- These can be
very addictive.

00:25.692 --> 00:28.402
- Who’s Mary Ellen Taylor?
- My mom.

00:28.445 --> 00:30.195
- I liked my life
the way it was, still do.

00:30.239 --> 00:31.569
- I don’t think
this guy’s an alien.

00:31.615 --> 00:32.915
- Did you notice
anything different

00:32.950 --> 00:34.700
about that new lunch lady?
She might be MIB.

00:34.743 --> 00:37.203
- MIB stole the baby
last night.

00:37.246 --> 00:39.406
What assholes,
exclamation mark!

00:41.917 --> 00:43.127
- Our first battery of exams

00:43.168 --> 00:45.248
haven’t detected
any extraterrestrial DNA,

00:45.295 --> 00:47.125
but our next round
of experimental tests--

00:47.172 --> 00:49.472
- Forget it.
I’m going in.

00:49.508 --> 00:50.798
- Yes, ma’am.

00:50.842 --> 00:52.642
I’ll inform the guards
to prepare the restraints.

00:52.678 --> 00:53.798
- Restraints?

00:53.845 --> 00:55.675
Don’t bother.

00:55.722 --> 00:57.642
He’s not an alien.

00:57.683 --> 00:59.233
None of them are.

01:00.852 --> 01:03.812
[door closes]

01:03.855 --> 01:06.725
[sighs]

01:06.775 --> 01:11.565
I remember being a kid,
the pranks we’d play.

01:11.613 --> 01:16.163
You’d do anything
to fit in, so I get it.

01:16.201 --> 01:19.701
It’s clear you look
like this dead boy.

01:21.373 --> 01:24.833
But whose idea was it for you
to pretend to be an alien?

01:24.876 --> 01:25.956
You can tell me.

01:26.003 --> 01:28.253
You won’t get in trouble.

01:30.382 --> 01:34.682
If you had any idea
the hundreds of subjects,

01:34.720 --> 01:36.510
the thousands of tests,

01:36.555 --> 01:40.145
then you would cut
the fake-alien shit!

01:41.143 --> 01:43.273
[sighs]

01:47.983 --> 01:50.363
[sighs]

01:50.402 --> 01:54.202
They’re real, you know.

01:54.239 --> 01:57.869
I saw them with my father...

01:57.909 --> 02:00.579
when I was about your age.

02:00.621 --> 02:03.541
[dramatic music]

02:03.582 --> 02:07.252
♪ ♪

02:07.294 --> 02:09.304
- Your eyes were
playing tricks on you.

02:09.338 --> 02:12.588
- I know what I saw.
Look at the damn photos.

02:12.633 --> 02:14.553
- Oh, we have.

02:14.593 --> 02:17.013
Could have been
a weather balloon.

02:17.054 --> 02:18.644
- Who the hell are you?

02:18.680 --> 02:20.680
- It’s just
and your daughter, right?

02:22.559 --> 02:26.019
- ♪ Leave it alone ♪

02:26.063 --> 02:29.153
♪ Give it a rest ♪

02:29.191 --> 02:33.611
- Dad, no!

02:33.654 --> 02:36.414
- ♪ Say what you needed
to say ♪

02:36.448 --> 02:40.198
♪ I got no happy ♪

02:40.243 --> 02:43.413
♪ In my head ♪

02:43.455 --> 02:47.385
♪ I miss that feeling ♪

02:47.417 --> 02:51.297
♪ I had ♪

02:51.338 --> 02:54.048
♪ That we’re all alone ♪

02:54.091 --> 02:55.881
- [squawks softly]

02:55.926 --> 02:58.426
- [shudders]

02:58.470 --> 03:01.430
[Brown Bird’s "Bilgewater"]

03:01.473 --> 03:04.603
[laid-back acoustic strumming]

03:04.643 --> 03:08.773
♪ ♪

03:08.814 --> 03:11.774
- My people began
as aquatic creatures.

03:11.817 --> 03:15.067
I am glad we grew legs
and started walking on land.

03:15.112 --> 03:16.992
I would not want to be a fish,

03:17.030 --> 03:19.450
in the same way
I do not want to be a human.

03:19.491 --> 03:22.991
So much of their lives
is out of their control.

03:23.036 --> 03:25.326
The fish swims forward
looking for food,

03:25.372 --> 03:29.002
and when they find it, they
get yanked out of their homes

03:29.042 --> 03:31.752
by a weird being,
measured and probed,

03:31.795 --> 03:34.965
and then thrown back
into their home.

03:35.006 --> 03:36.716
It is not the fish’s fault.

03:36.758 --> 03:40.508
If I was hungry and I saw
a pizza on a hook,

03:40.554 --> 03:43.514
I might not be able to control
myself either.

03:44.850 --> 03:48.310
- [breathes deeply]
- It’s my fault.

03:48.353 --> 03:50.483
I spent my whole life
trying to protect you.

03:50.522 --> 03:52.612
I should have told you
what I knew about your mother

03:52.649 --> 03:55.109
a long time ago.

03:55.152 --> 03:57.322
- Now I understand
why you didn’t.

03:57.362 --> 04:00.992
- You know, I met her
when she joined our band.

04:01.032 --> 04:03.832
She was pregnant already.

04:03.869 --> 04:05.499
So you were, like...

04:05.537 --> 04:07.287
[chuckles]
The fifth member.

04:08.874 --> 04:10.334
- Did you know my father?

04:10.375 --> 04:13.495
- Mary-Ellen kept that
to herself.

04:13.545 --> 04:16.515
I ended up watching
you most of the time.

04:16.548 --> 04:19.178
Then one day
she was just gone.

04:19.217 --> 04:21.757
- How do you just leave
a kid like that on a doorstep

04:21.803 --> 04:24.513
and not care at all?
- I don’t know.

04:24.556 --> 04:28.516
My bandmates told me
to call CPS, but...

04:28.560 --> 04:32.150
I called
an adoption lawyer instead.

04:32.189 --> 04:34.149
- You’re too kind
for your own good.

04:34.191 --> 04:36.651
- It wasn’t kindness;

04:36.693 --> 04:37.903
it was love.

04:37.944 --> 04:40.864
You were yourself, Asta,
the day you were born.

04:40.906 --> 04:43.486
I can’t make people see
how special you are,

04:43.533 --> 04:45.703
but I always have.

04:45.744 --> 04:49.044
I lost a drummer,
but I gained a daughter.

04:49.080 --> 04:51.370
More than a fair trade,
I’d say.

04:51.416 --> 04:55.036
[sentimental music]

04:55.086 --> 04:58.046
- Thanks, Dad.
- Yeah.

04:58.089 --> 05:00.429
♪ ♪

05:00.467 --> 05:03.547
[indistinct chatter]

05:05.597 --> 05:07.677
- Oh, I thought I heard voices.

05:07.724 --> 05:10.184
Morning, Kayla.
- Ben, hi

05:10.227 --> 05:11.887
- Kayla asked me
to help her with a case.

05:11.937 --> 05:13.727
- Honey, that’s amazing.

05:13.772 --> 05:15.902
See, I knew you’d back into law
when the timing was right.

05:15.941 --> 05:17.071
What’s the case?

05:17.108 --> 05:18.778
- I am helping Kayla’s law firm

05:18.819 --> 05:20.779
get a temporary
restraining order

05:20.821 --> 05:24.201
to stop the resort
from moving forward.

05:24.241 --> 05:25.781
- Huh.

05:27.786 --> 05:29.116
Great.

05:29.162 --> 05:30.712
Can I get you some more coffee?

05:30.747 --> 05:33.327
- Oh, that’d be nice, honey.
- Mm-hmm.

05:33.375 --> 05:37.175
- So, um, the judge is gonna
decide whether we’ve proven...

05:37.212 --> 05:40.592
[coffee grinder
whirring loudly]

05:40.632 --> 05:42.182
Um, whether we’ve proven...

05:42.217 --> 05:45.047
[coffee grinder
whirring loudly]

05:50.267 --> 05:51.597
- Sorry, Kayla.

05:51.643 --> 05:54.103
- [chuckles] Look, listen,
the key to all of this

05:54.145 --> 05:56.725
is just that we’re gonna prove
that the environmental impact--

05:56.773 --> 06:00.113
[coffee grinder
whirring loudly]

06:00.151 --> 06:01.241
If we’ve proven--

06:01.278 --> 06:02.898
[coffee grinder
whirring intermittently]

06:02.946 --> 06:04.106
Irreparable...

06:04.155 --> 06:05.445
environmental--

06:05.490 --> 06:08.410
[coffee grinder
whirring loudly]

06:14.165 --> 06:15.745
- Ben!

06:15.792 --> 06:17.252
[whirring stops]

06:17.294 --> 06:18.634
- Did you say my name?

06:18.670 --> 06:20.380
- I know what you’re doing.

06:20.422 --> 06:22.382
- Barista-ing?

06:22.424 --> 06:23.974
- You know what?
I’m just going to head out.

06:24.009 --> 06:25.799
I’ll let you know
what the judge says,

06:25.844 --> 06:28.104
and, um, I’ll take a rain check
on that coffee.

06:28.138 --> 06:29.508
- Oh.

06:29.556 --> 06:31.806
- And the vacuuming you
were probably about to do.

06:31.850 --> 06:33.270
- Yeah.

06:33.310 --> 06:36.690
[door opens, closes]

06:36.730 --> 06:38.900
- Was that the most mature
thing you’ve ever done?

06:38.940 --> 06:40.820
- Mm, top three.

06:40.859 --> 06:43.609
- Look, I know we’re
on different sides

06:43.653 --> 06:45.413
of this resort thing.
- Mm-hmm.

06:45.447 --> 06:48.407
- Maybe it wasn’t fair of me to
have a meeting like that here.

06:48.450 --> 06:50.160
- Thank you.

06:50.201 --> 06:52.291
- So we make a pact.

06:52.329 --> 06:54.159
The second we walk
in that door,

06:54.205 --> 06:56.075
we don’t talk about the resort.

06:56.124 --> 06:58.294
[dramatic music]

06:58.335 --> 07:00.845
- [sighs]
Deal.

07:00.879 --> 07:02.299
- Okay.

07:02.339 --> 07:05.089
- [growling]

07:05.133 --> 07:06.513
So stupid.

07:06.551 --> 07:08.681
- Hey, you wanted to see me?

07:08.720 --> 07:12.010
- [clears throat]
Yes, uh...

07:12.057 --> 07:15.307
I have, uh, something
that I wanted to tell you,

07:15.352 --> 07:18.192
but I don’t know how,
so I wrote it in a letter.

07:18.229 --> 07:20.109
- Okay, just tell me.

07:26.071 --> 07:27.321
- Okay.

07:27.364 --> 07:31.034
"Dear, Asta, the Greys
are here to kill us all"?

07:31.076 --> 07:32.326
That’s your opening?

07:32.369 --> 07:34.079
- I wanted to get
your attention.

07:34.120 --> 07:35.870
- Good job.
It worked.

07:35.914 --> 07:38.374
- Mm.
- [sighs] Are we all gonna die?

07:38.416 --> 07:40.326
Again?
- Mm.

07:40.377 --> 07:42.297
- Why are they here?
- I do not know.

07:42.337 --> 07:46.507
It all happened very fast.
He threatened me and then left.

07:46.549 --> 07:48.509
You are a Grey.

07:48.551 --> 07:50.551
- Yes, and you are...

07:50.595 --> 07:53.675
[speaking in native language]

07:59.688 --> 08:02.728
- It’s funny to hear it
in your accent.

08:02.774 --> 08:06.364
I will find these Greys.
Do not worry.

08:06.403 --> 08:08.613
- You drew the Earth exploding.

08:08.655 --> 08:11.665
But, yeah, sure,
nothing to worry about.

08:11.700 --> 08:14.580
♪ ♪

08:14.619 --> 08:17.369
- But the artistry is...

08:17.414 --> 08:19.504
pretty undeniable.

08:19.541 --> 08:20.921
- You’ve reached
Detective Lena Torres,

08:20.959 --> 08:22.669
Jessup PD--
please leave a message.

08:22.711 --> 08:24.591
[line beeps]
- Uh, hello, Detective.

08:24.629 --> 08:26.589
It’s, uh,
Mike Thompson calling.

08:26.631 --> 08:28.341
Uh, actually,
I heard on the scanner

08:28.383 --> 08:31.183
that you guys were dealing
with a gang of turkey thieves.

08:31.219 --> 08:32.929
I just wanted
to make sure you know

08:32.971 --> 08:35.771
that we can offer help or
reinforcements if you need it.

08:35.807 --> 08:37.767
Um, actually, to me,
it’s kind of crazy

08:37.809 --> 08:39.809
somebody would want
to steal something

08:39.853 --> 08:42.613
that looks like a peacock
had sex with a loose red sock.

08:42.647 --> 08:45.687
But, um, anyway, um,
I was calling

08:45.734 --> 08:47.404
because I was just wondering
what you was up to, and--

08:47.444 --> 08:48.534
- Oh, good morning, sir.

08:48.570 --> 08:49.950
I didn’t know
you were here yet.

08:49.988 --> 08:51.608
Here’s your bear claw.
- Just one second, please.

08:51.656 --> 08:52.986
Uh, sorry about that,
Detective.

08:53.033 --> 08:54.993
Anyway, like I said, you
can give me a call sometime.

08:55.035 --> 08:56.375
All right, thank you.
Bye-bye.

08:56.411 --> 08:57.701
- I knew it.

08:57.746 --> 08:59.156
You two are gonna have
ten babies together.

08:59.205 --> 09:00.785
- [stammers]
Deputy, what are you doing?

09:00.832 --> 09:02.832
I hadn’t hung up yet.
- No, I’m--

09:02.876 --> 09:04.746
- I was right on the brink
of leaving the perfect message,

09:04.794 --> 09:06.804
and then as I’m about
to nail my triple axel,

09:06.838 --> 09:08.588
you come up behind me
with a lead pipe

09:08.631 --> 09:09.841
and take out both my knees?

09:09.883 --> 09:12.763
- But I only accidentally
smashed your knees,

09:12.802 --> 09:14.432
and it really
wasn’t a lead pipe.

09:14.471 --> 09:15.851
Like, it was more
of a soft wooden bat,

09:15.889 --> 09:17.429
because women like babies.

09:17.474 --> 09:19.644
I’m just--I’m gonna--

09:19.684 --> 09:23.154
I’m gonna leave this here.

09:23.188 --> 09:25.148
- [mumbles]

09:25.190 --> 09:27.980
♪ ♪

09:28.026 --> 09:30.436
[sighs]

09:30.487 --> 09:34.067
- [sighs, groans]

09:34.115 --> 09:36.825
[winces]

09:36.868 --> 09:39.578
[soft music playing]

09:39.621 --> 09:41.661
- D’arcy.

09:41.706 --> 09:46.666
♪ ♪

09:46.711 --> 09:48.551
- Good morning, champ.

09:48.588 --> 09:51.338
- Hi.

09:51.382 --> 09:52.512
Is it morning?

09:52.550 --> 09:55.010
It’s, like, 11:30.

09:55.053 --> 09:57.183
[sighs]
Have you seen my blender lid?

09:57.222 --> 09:58.722
- No.

09:58.765 --> 10:01.145
- It’s always in this drawer.
You sure you didn’t move it?

10:01.184 --> 10:02.314
I have a whole system.

10:02.352 --> 10:04.692
- I never pegged you
for a system person.

10:04.729 --> 10:07.359
I also said "good morning."

10:07.398 --> 10:09.978
- [sighs] You did.

10:10.026 --> 10:11.986
- [chuckles]

10:12.028 --> 10:13.318
- Mmm.

10:13.363 --> 10:15.703
♪ ♪

10:15.740 --> 10:17.370
Wait, do you think I’m messy?

10:17.408 --> 10:19.198
- No, not at all.

10:19.244 --> 10:21.504
I like you being a neat freak
about your blender.

10:21.538 --> 10:23.078
- [chuckles] Neat freak?

10:23.123 --> 10:24.873
I’m a neat freak
because I put things

10:24.916 --> 10:26.746
in the drawer
where they belong?

10:26.793 --> 10:29.053
[chuckles]
I mean, come on, you know...

10:29.087 --> 10:32.257
Is the carpenter
who puts separate containers

10:32.298 --> 10:34.758
for the forks and knives
also a neat freak?

10:34.801 --> 10:36.221
You know who was
a real neat freak?

10:36.261 --> 10:37.681
Whoever invented numbers.

10:37.720 --> 10:39.180
You know, each one
is its own separate thing.

10:39.222 --> 10:40.562
What a neat freak.

10:40.598 --> 10:42.888
- You really gonna rant
at me about a blender lid?

10:42.934 --> 10:44.524
- I just need you
to help me find it.

10:44.561 --> 10:50.521
♪ ♪

10:50.567 --> 10:52.527
- Here.
- Oh.

10:52.569 --> 10:54.899
Huh.
Thank you.

10:54.946 --> 10:57.446
You are like my little
appliances truffle pig.

10:57.490 --> 11:00.830
♪ ♪

11:00.869 --> 11:03.659
[blender whirring]

11:03.705 --> 11:05.045
Mm.

11:05.081 --> 11:07.921
♪ ♪

11:07.959 --> 11:10.539
Mmm, so good.

11:10.587 --> 11:12.797
You want one?
- Are you okay?

11:12.839 --> 11:15.089
You seem a little
all over the place lately.

11:15.133 --> 11:19.723
- Um, just in my head
about the hardpack tournament.

11:19.762 --> 11:22.222
Competition mode--
it’s an intense mode.

11:22.265 --> 11:24.185
- Ah, if you’re stressed,
we’ll skip tonight.

11:24.225 --> 11:25.885
- No, no way.

11:25.935 --> 11:28.935
Sir, dinner is on.

11:28.980 --> 11:31.270
Mwah!
Gonna see you tonight.

11:31.316 --> 11:33.276
Gonna make me something
with protein in it.

11:33.318 --> 11:35.438
- [laughs]

11:35.486 --> 11:38.566
- Hey, Deputy.

11:38.615 --> 11:40.285
- Any word
from Detective Torres?

11:40.325 --> 11:43.375
- No, Deputy.
- Maybe she’s busy.

11:43.411 --> 11:45.161
- Maybe she don’t want to have
ten babies.

11:45.205 --> 11:47.425
Anyway, uh, weren’t you
trying to get in touch

11:47.457 --> 11:49.077
with that Alien Tracker guy?

11:49.125 --> 11:51.125
- Oh, I gave up.

11:51.169 --> 11:52.589
I sent 60 emails.

11:52.629 --> 11:55.209
He didn’t respond to even one.

11:55.256 --> 11:57.376
You know, I spent all this time
putting him on a pedestal.

11:57.425 --> 11:59.085
He’s probably just a jerk.

11:59.135 --> 12:01.675
- Okay, well, he’s also here.

12:04.057 --> 12:07.017
- It was 62 emails, actually.

12:08.937 --> 12:11.147
Would you care to have lunch
with a jerk?

12:11.189 --> 12:12.899
- [gasps softly]

12:22.909 --> 12:24.739
- We’ve got a problem.

12:24.786 --> 12:27.196
Uh, apparently, a couple
of power-hungry lawyers

12:27.247 --> 12:29.417
are filing
a restraining order

12:29.457 --> 12:31.707
to temporarily stop
the resort project.

12:31.751 --> 12:33.171
- Really?
How you know that?

12:33.211 --> 12:35.251
- Well, let’s just say
you don’t become mayor

12:35.296 --> 12:37.166
without having a few ears out
in the community.

12:37.215 --> 12:39.015
- Kate’s one of the lawyers.
- She sure is.

12:39.050 --> 12:40.340
- Okay.
- Yes.

12:40.385 --> 12:42.055
And I would blame that
for my stress headache,

12:42.095 --> 12:43.355
but I’ve had that
since I was six.

12:43.388 --> 12:44.388
- Okay, you know what?

12:44.430 --> 12:45.890
You done come
to the right place,

12:45.932 --> 12:47.562
’cause you happen
to be in the presence

12:47.600 --> 12:49.190
of a professional masseur.

12:49.227 --> 12:50.767
Here, go ahead.
Take a seat.

12:50.812 --> 12:52.902
Take a seat.
Go ahead.

12:52.939 --> 12:54.729
- You went to massage school?
- I sure did.

12:54.774 --> 12:56.904
I graduated top of my class.
- Hmm.

12:56.943 --> 12:58.693
- Taught myself
in my own kitchen.

12:58.736 --> 13:00.066
- Is it too late
to stand back up?

13:00.113 --> 13:01.613
- No, no, you’re fine.
Don’t worry.

13:01.656 --> 13:02.776
I learned
the old-fashioned way.

13:02.824 --> 13:04.244
See, I practiced on cats.

13:04.284 --> 13:06.294
If you can massage
a cat at 3:00 a. m.

13:06.327 --> 13:08.947
without being scratched to
death or waking your neighbor,

13:08.997 --> 13:10.367
you graduate.

13:10.415 --> 13:12.005
You know, the more feral,
the better.

13:12.041 --> 13:13.671
I remember for my masters,

13:13.710 --> 13:15.540
I found this cat
in an alleyway.

13:15.586 --> 13:18.916
I still can’t grow hair on my
left forearm, but I graduated.

13:18.965 --> 13:21.805
- Ow, well, uh,
the back pain has drowned out

13:21.843 --> 13:23.303
the head pain, so thank you.

13:23.344 --> 13:24.804
- Oh, you’re welcome.
- Very much.

13:24.846 --> 13:26.096
- Now that you’ve
got a clear head,

13:26.139 --> 13:27.519
you can start
thinking about how

13:27.557 --> 13:29.597
to get Kate off of this resort
thing when you get home.

13:29.642 --> 13:31.142
- Uh, well, see, that’s--
that’s the problem.

13:31.185 --> 13:32.685
I can’t.

13:32.729 --> 13:35.019
We agreed not to talk about
the resort when we’re at home.

13:35.064 --> 13:36.824
- That’s a good idea.
That’s best for your marriage.

13:36.858 --> 13:39.028
I, on the other hand, am not
married to either one of you.

13:39.068 --> 13:41.698
Look, invite me over to dinner.

13:41.738 --> 13:43.568
I accept.
I’ll see you tonight.

13:43.614 --> 13:48.084
- Uh, I’m having a hard time
turning my head to the left?

13:48.119 --> 13:49.829
- Yes, you know what?
The cats had the same problem.

13:49.871 --> 13:51.331
Try this.

13:51.372 --> 13:53.622
Try hunching your back
over like this and hissing.

13:53.666 --> 13:56.286
I’ll see you later.

13:56.336 --> 13:57.996
- W-what?

13:58.046 --> 14:01.006
[indistinct chatter]

14:01.049 --> 14:04.009
[soft music playing]

14:04.052 --> 14:06.762
- I have figured out
how to stop the Greys.

14:06.804 --> 14:08.064
- What?

14:08.097 --> 14:10.807
That’s great.
What are you gonna do?

14:10.850 --> 14:12.520
- There is
another alien convention

14:12.560 --> 14:13.690
in New Mexico next week.

14:13.728 --> 14:15.268
It will be filled with humans

14:15.313 --> 14:17.693
that have been probed
and implanted

14:17.732 --> 14:20.072
by those horrible
Grey creatures.

14:20.109 --> 14:21.489
- That’s true.

14:21.527 --> 14:24.817
You could use those people
to, what, track the Greys?

14:24.864 --> 14:28.374
- No, I will kidnap the humans
and rip out their implants

14:28.409 --> 14:31.749
and then re-implant them
in professional show dogs.

14:31.788 --> 14:32.868
[laughs]

14:32.914 --> 14:34.334
- What?
- Mm-hmm.

14:34.374 --> 14:36.504
The Greys will be so confused.

14:36.542 --> 14:40.342
"Why is that human
that I abducted

14:40.380 --> 14:43.340
running around in circles
and jumping over gates?"

14:43.383 --> 14:47.143
That will stop them
for three to five minutes.

14:47.178 --> 14:48.888
- We need to start
thinking about a plan B.

14:48.930 --> 14:50.640
- Mm, what?

14:50.681 --> 14:51.771
- Yeah.

14:51.808 --> 14:52.848
Hey.

14:52.892 --> 14:54.602
That guy
looks an awful lot like--

14:54.644 --> 14:57.314
[gasps] Oh, my God,
that’s the Alien Tracker.

14:57.355 --> 14:59.065
He’s sitting in a booth
with Liv.

14:59.107 --> 15:01.147
Why is he with Liv?
- Is he ordering pie?

15:01.192 --> 15:02.482
- I don’t know.
Let’s go.

15:02.527 --> 15:05.607
- I was here earlier.
There’s only one left.

15:07.573 --> 15:09.663
He has a dessert menu,
the son of a bitch!

15:09.700 --> 15:11.290
- Oh, God.

15:11.327 --> 15:14.367
- The ship was gone by the time
the other kids came back,

15:14.414 --> 15:18.794
but, somehow, in that moment,
I felt like--

15:18.835 --> 15:21.595
- You felt your world expand

15:21.629 --> 15:24.419
beyond anything
you ever imagined possible.

15:24.465 --> 15:27.335
- Wow. Exactly.

15:27.385 --> 15:30.935
But the thing that I remember
most was feeling alone.

15:30.972 --> 15:34.222
I knew no one would believe me,
except my Aunt Cathy.

15:34.267 --> 15:36.387
But her favorite shirt
was a straitjacket.

15:36.436 --> 15:39.646
- Well, that’s why
so few come forward.

15:39.689 --> 15:41.939
You know, I’m producing
a documentary

15:41.983 --> 15:44.533
where experiencers
share their stories.

15:44.569 --> 15:46.779
People need to know
they’re not alone.

15:46.821 --> 15:48.071
- You’re so noble.

15:48.114 --> 15:49.954
You’re like a lion.

15:49.991 --> 15:51.741
- Would you be interested
in participating?

15:51.784 --> 15:53.374
- Oh, I couldn’t.

15:53.411 --> 15:55.961
I would be so worried
about what everyone might think

15:55.997 --> 15:57.867
that my elbows
would start to sweat.

15:57.915 --> 16:00.035
They’re--
they’re sweating now.

16:01.294 --> 16:03.594
- [groans]
[door opens]

16:03.629 --> 16:06.719
- Hey, you can’t just come
back here--it’s unsanitary.

16:06.757 --> 16:08.127
- Okay, Dad,

16:08.176 --> 16:09.546
we need to stay here
until this guy leaves, okay?

16:09.594 --> 16:11.264
He knows that Harry’s an alien,

16:11.304 --> 16:13.514
and he might recognize me
from the convention.

16:13.556 --> 16:16.266
- Dan, do not sell
that bad man any pie.

16:16.309 --> 16:18.389
- Hmm.
- [sighs, gasps]

16:18.436 --> 16:19.686
- Excuse me.

16:20.813 --> 16:22.193
- Ah!

16:22.231 --> 16:24.361
- What’s going on?
- He saw me. Give me a fork.

16:24.400 --> 16:26.990
I need to stab him in
the neck--and anyone who saw.

16:27.028 --> 16:30.068
I have a lot of necks to stab.
- You’re not stabbing anyone!

16:30.114 --> 16:31.414
- No.
- She’s right.

16:31.449 --> 16:32.529
Go out the back.

16:32.575 --> 16:34.545
- What’s going on?
Is everything okay?

16:34.577 --> 16:37.287
[dramatic music]

16:37.330 --> 16:39.290
- I have to check
something out--I’ll be back.

16:39.332 --> 16:40.792
- Is checking tracking?

16:40.833 --> 16:42.503
Are you alien checking?

16:42.543 --> 16:43.843
I’ll be here.

16:43.878 --> 16:51.008
♪ ♪

16:57.058 --> 16:59.638
[pop rock music playing]

16:59.685 --> 17:01.145
- Hey, Liv.

17:01.187 --> 17:03.807
Were you just here with friend?
- Oh, no.

17:03.856 --> 17:07.026
It might be early
for the F word,

17:07.068 --> 17:09.188
but he did share
some childhood-trauma stuff.

17:09.237 --> 17:12.197
- Mm.
- Plus, I do know his birthday,

17:12.240 --> 17:14.070
favorite color, and moon sign.

17:14.116 --> 17:16.946
Holy crap, I’m friends
with the Alien Tracker.

17:16.994 --> 17:18.204
- The Alien Tracker--

17:18.246 --> 17:20.326
isn’t that that podcast
you listen to?

17:20.373 --> 17:22.463
Like, he chases Martians
or something?

17:22.500 --> 17:25.000
- Yeah, but Peter is
so much more than that.

17:25.044 --> 17:26.344
He literally wrote the book

17:26.379 --> 17:28.299
on government
alien conspiracies.

17:28.339 --> 17:31.129
- Mm, so is he here
visiting his number-one fan

17:31.175 --> 17:33.795
or here on business?

17:33.844 --> 17:35.974
- He thinks that there
might be alien activity

17:36.013 --> 17:37.223
right here in Patience.

17:37.265 --> 17:39.485
He’s checking out a lead now.

17:39.517 --> 17:41.097
How exciting is that?

17:41.143 --> 17:43.483
- Wow, that is really exciting.

17:43.521 --> 17:46.111
Man, he means business.

17:46.148 --> 17:47.938
I wouldn’t want
to be that alien.

17:47.984 --> 17:51.074
[Belle and Sebastian’s
"Sukie in the Graveyard"]

17:51.112 --> 17:53.322
- Hi, Dr. Vanderspeigle.

17:53.364 --> 17:56.834
Can I ask you about making
an appointment for--

17:56.867 --> 17:58.657
- ♪ Sukie was the kid ♪

17:58.703 --> 18:00.703
♪ She liked to hang out
in the graveyard ♪

18:00.746 --> 18:01.866
- Excuse me.

18:01.914 --> 18:03.374
- ♪ She did brass rubbings ♪

18:03.416 --> 18:06.376
♪ She learned
she never had to press hard ♪

18:06.419 --> 18:08.209
♪ When she was finished
hanging out ♪

18:08.254 --> 18:09.804
♪ She was all alone ♪

18:09.839 --> 18:12.009
♪ She decided that she better
check in at home ♪

18:12.049 --> 18:14.219
♪ There was an awful row
between her mum and dad ♪

18:14.260 --> 18:16.720
♪ They said she hadn’t done
this, she hadn’t done that ♪

18:16.762 --> 18:19.012
♪ If she wanted to remain
inside the family home ♪

18:19.056 --> 18:21.516
♪ She’d have to toe the line,
she’d have to give it a go ♪

18:21.559 --> 18:24.519
♪ It didn’t suit Sukie,
she took her things and left ♪

18:24.562 --> 18:28.862
♪ ♪

18:28.899 --> 18:30.529
- [chuckles]

18:30.568 --> 18:32.488
- ♪ She liked to hang out
in the graveyard ♪

18:32.528 --> 18:34.398
♪ ♪

18:34.447 --> 18:36.947
[objects clatter]

18:36.991 --> 18:38.911
Ah.

18:38.951 --> 18:40.411
I should have killed you

18:40.453 --> 18:42.753
when you were begging me
not to rip your neck open

18:42.788 --> 18:44.328
like a stupid baby.

18:44.373 --> 18:46.043
- Sometimes I wish you had.

18:46.083 --> 18:47.923
The only thing
that kept me going

18:47.960 --> 18:52.010
was the incontrovertible fact
that the next time I saw you,

18:52.048 --> 18:56.548
you would be the one
cowering in fear.

18:56.594 --> 18:58.054
[electricity buzzing]

18:58.095 --> 18:59.925
- I did not want
to murder this man

18:59.972 --> 19:01.772
in the middle of town.

19:01.807 --> 19:03.767
It is going to be messy
for the people

19:03.809 --> 19:05.269
who clean up dead bodies.

19:05.311 --> 19:07.941
I’ll write "sorry"
on the wall in his blood.

19:07.980 --> 19:09.900
[electricity buzzing]

19:09.940 --> 19:12.070
- [growls]

19:13.778 --> 19:16.948
- Witness, he--he was texting
while walking.

19:16.989 --> 19:18.819
Sustained, Your Honor.

19:18.866 --> 19:20.906
Exhibit, bailiff.

19:20.951 --> 19:23.081
- It’s okay, ma’am.

19:23.120 --> 19:25.250
It’ll take more than that
to take me out.

19:25.289 --> 19:27.169
- [sighs in relief]

19:27.208 --> 19:30.038
Oh, there you are.

19:32.338 --> 19:36.298
- Your underwear
is arousing me sexually.

19:36.342 --> 19:38.432
Let me buy you a beer,

19:38.469 --> 19:41.759
uh, woman that I just met.

19:41.806 --> 19:44.806
- [chuckles]

19:44.850 --> 19:47.310
[indistinct chatter]

19:47.353 --> 19:50.983
So...this is finally
happening, huh?

19:51.023 --> 19:52.613
- Mm.
- I remember that pap smear.

19:52.650 --> 19:54.860
You were down there
for quite a while.

19:54.902 --> 19:56.032
- [chuckles awkwardly]

19:56.070 --> 19:58.070
- I think you saw
something you liked.

19:58.114 --> 19:59.244
I get it.
- Oh, no!

19:59.281 --> 20:01.201
We have changed.

20:01.242 --> 20:02.952
We have grown apart.

20:02.993 --> 20:06.503
The mature thing for us to do
is to go our way separately.

20:06.539 --> 20:08.579
It is not me.
It is you.

20:08.624 --> 20:09.544
It is me.

20:12.962 --> 20:15.132
[door opens]
- Well, crap.

20:15.172 --> 20:18.012
Can you spot me a tequila?
- Sure.

20:18.050 --> 20:21.260
Yeah, just got diz-numped.

20:23.472 --> 20:24.812
Hello.

20:24.849 --> 20:27.139
[soft music playing]

20:27.184 --> 20:30.814
- I saved your breakfast.

20:30.855 --> 20:33.825
The busboy tried to take it.
I had to show him my gun.

20:33.858 --> 20:35.148
- Yeah, I’m not hungry.

20:35.192 --> 20:37.152
I grabbed a sandwich
at the deli.

20:37.194 --> 20:38.494
- Oh.

20:38.529 --> 20:41.029
Anyway, you ran off so fast.

20:41.073 --> 20:42.493
Did you find something?

20:42.533 --> 20:44.663
[whispering]
Uh, was it the alien?

20:44.702 --> 20:46.122
- [sighs]

20:46.162 --> 20:48.212
You know, people think you have
to be alone somewhere

20:48.247 --> 20:49.997
for them to get to you.

20:50.040 --> 20:52.670
My wife and I were on
a crowded bus in New York City,

20:52.710 --> 20:56.880
and they ripped my child out
of my wife’s pregnant belly.

20:56.922 --> 21:00.092
I’m not gonna let anyone else
suffer like we did.

21:00.134 --> 21:02.724
So, even if there was an alien
standing right next to us,

21:02.762 --> 21:04.432
I would not tell you.

21:04.472 --> 21:06.602
And I wouldn’t take
any action...

21:06.640 --> 21:09.940
not with any innocent
people around.

21:09.977 --> 21:12.347
- That is so admirable.

21:12.396 --> 21:13.686
Did I say that already?

21:13.731 --> 21:15.691
I feel like
I’m repeating myself.

21:15.733 --> 21:17.363
My elbows are hot again.

21:17.401 --> 21:19.531
- So what did you
want to show me?

21:19.570 --> 21:21.570
- Oh.

21:21.614 --> 21:27.204
♪ ♪

21:27.244 --> 21:31.464
I’ve been documenting possible
alien activity in Patience,

21:31.499 --> 21:33.289
possible UFO sightings,

21:33.334 --> 21:36.594
you know,
the stuff people call in about.

21:36.629 --> 21:40.219
♪ ♪

21:40.257 --> 21:43.387
[dramatic music]

21:43.427 --> 21:44.967
- What is this?

21:45.012 --> 21:47.222
- Oh, that was a hoax
started by the mayor’s son.

21:47.264 --> 21:49.434
I already questioned him.
It was nothing.

21:49.475 --> 21:52.065
Unless it means something
to you.

21:52.102 --> 21:54.232
- No.

21:54.271 --> 21:56.941
May I hang on to this
for a bit?

21:56.982 --> 21:58.732
- You like my book?

21:58.776 --> 22:01.236
Of course, yes,
you can hang on to it.

22:03.072 --> 22:04.362
Sweaty.

22:04.406 --> 22:07.116
- Let’s catch up tonight,
2100 hours.

22:07.159 --> 22:08.659
Is there a tavern around here?

22:08.702 --> 22:11.082
- Yeah, we have a pub.
It’s called The 59.

22:11.121 --> 22:12.461
- I prefer a tavern.

22:12.498 --> 22:14.918
- Is there a difference?
- There is a big difference.

22:14.959 --> 22:16.879
- Oh, we just have a pub.

22:18.212 --> 22:19.422
- I suppose I can go with that.

22:19.463 --> 22:21.383
- Thank you.
Have a nice day.

22:21.423 --> 22:23.883
- I’ll see you there.
You stay safe, now.

22:29.890 --> 22:33.100
- Okay.

22:33.143 --> 22:37.113
Okay, these are for heartburn.

22:37.147 --> 22:39.777
These are
for my cat’s heartburn.

22:39.817 --> 22:42.987
Ooh, I don’t know
what this one is.

22:43.028 --> 22:45.358
[coughs] Oh.

22:45.406 --> 22:47.366
I think that one was a bead.

22:47.408 --> 22:49.118
- Judes, my knee is on fire.

22:49.159 --> 22:50.949
I need the pain meds
that you took

22:50.995 --> 22:52.415
after you fell off the roof.

22:52.454 --> 22:56.124
- Yeah, roofing looks like
it’d be so easy, yeah?

22:56.166 --> 22:57.666
[scoffs] It’s not.

22:57.710 --> 23:00.460
[sighs]
Ooh, maybe these ones.

23:00.504 --> 23:03.134
Do you have dry mouth...
- Yes.

23:03.173 --> 23:04.843
- Constipation...
- So much.

23:04.884 --> 23:07.304
- And mood swings?
- Oh, my God, give me those.

23:07.344 --> 23:09.354
That’s it.

23:09.388 --> 23:11.468
- Can--can I keep
just, like, one,

23:11.515 --> 23:13.515
just in case
I swallow any more beads?

23:13.559 --> 23:16.649
- No, just don’t eat beads.

23:16.687 --> 23:18.187
- Wow.

23:18.230 --> 23:20.270
Are you, like, a doctor?

23:23.110 --> 23:24.990
[door closes]

23:25.029 --> 23:27.609
- [scarfing]

23:27.656 --> 23:30.986
- What are you doing here?

23:31.035 --> 23:32.795
Oh, you should be hiding.

23:34.872 --> 23:36.372
- I’m an alien.

23:36.415 --> 23:38.325
Aliens do not hide from humans.

23:38.375 --> 23:40.035
- Well, you should.

23:40.085 --> 23:41.545
I talked to Liv.

23:41.587 --> 23:44.007
This whole Alien Tracker thing
is not just for show.

23:44.048 --> 23:46.048
He’s an expert on aliens.

23:46.091 --> 23:47.431
He even wrote a book

23:47.468 --> 23:50.388
about some secret alien
government program.

23:50.429 --> 23:53.179
Harry, he could hurt you.

23:53.223 --> 23:54.933
- Could you tell
the angry nurse

23:54.975 --> 23:59.095
to make a ham sandwich
next time?

23:59.146 --> 24:01.856
- I feel like maybe you’re not
taking this very seriously.

24:01.899 --> 24:03.689
- What could
the Alien Tracker know

24:03.734 --> 24:05.534
about aliens that I do not?

24:05.569 --> 24:09.739
- He knows about a secret
government alien program,

24:09.782 --> 24:11.742
which means
he could know anything,

24:11.784 --> 24:14.124
about your people, the Greys.

24:14.161 --> 24:15.541
Who knows?

24:15.579 --> 24:17.119
It’s not safe for you
to wander around here.

24:17.164 --> 24:18.584
You really should
go home and hide.

24:18.624 --> 24:21.384
- Humans hide.
Aliens hunt.

24:21.418 --> 24:22.788
If the Alien Tracker

24:22.836 --> 24:24.796
has gained insider knowledge
on the Greys,

24:24.838 --> 24:27.008
perhaps I can use him
to get to them.

24:27.049 --> 24:28.719
- Okay, I will go.

24:28.759 --> 24:30.219
- Thank you.

24:30.260 --> 24:32.180
- Do you want my pickle?

24:32.221 --> 24:33.811
It’s floppy.

24:33.847 --> 24:35.057
- No.

24:35.099 --> 24:36.219
- All right.

24:36.266 --> 24:39.226
[mysterious music]

24:39.269 --> 24:46.439
♪ ♪

24:48.445 --> 24:51.355
[crunches]

24:51.407 --> 24:56.157
♪ ♪

24:56.203 --> 24:58.293
- Max.

24:58.330 --> 25:00.750
I’m sorry.
I didn’t mean to startle you.

25:00.791 --> 25:03.841
My name is Peter Bach.
- You’re the Alien Tracker!

25:03.877 --> 25:06.247
- I need your help
finding someone...

25:06.296 --> 25:09.256
or maybe I should say
"something."

25:09.299 --> 25:11.799
- Uh, that’s just
a joke I made up.

25:11.844 --> 25:14.764
I’m really funny for my size.
[chuckles awkwardly]

25:14.805 --> 25:16.935
- Well, I-I don’t think
it’s a joke.

25:16.974 --> 25:19.644
This looks exactly
like an extraterrestrial

25:19.685 --> 25:22.815
that I saw here today.

25:22.855 --> 25:25.985
- You can really see them?
- Just like you.

25:26.025 --> 25:30.325
♪ ♪

25:30.362 --> 25:33.872
- No, I told you--
I just made it up.

25:33.907 --> 25:36.617
- I remember when I saw
my first alien

25:36.660 --> 25:38.120
that had a humanoid form.

25:38.162 --> 25:41.672
But when I saw his face...
like a snake.

25:41.707 --> 25:44.247
- Whoa.
An Alpha Draconian.

25:44.293 --> 25:47.803
- His gaze bore
right into mine,

25:47.838 --> 25:50.508
but no one else could see
what I saw.

25:50.549 --> 25:52.299
To them, he looked
just like a regular person.

25:52.342 --> 25:54.892
I thought I was going crazy.

25:54.928 --> 25:57.468
Now, you’ve probably been
called crazy before. too.

25:57.514 --> 25:58.934
- Yeah.

25:58.974 --> 26:01.184
- Why don’t you
tell me who he is?

26:01.226 --> 26:04.476
♪ ♪

26:04.521 --> 26:06.941
I can’t.
- Max, listen to me.

26:06.982 --> 26:09.322
I understand.
You’re trying to protect him.

26:09.359 --> 26:10.779
H-he’s probably
got you convinced

26:10.819 --> 26:12.319
that he’s your friend.

26:12.362 --> 26:15.322
But aliens don’t come
all this way to be our friends.

26:15.365 --> 26:17.325
They come here to do us harm.

26:17.367 --> 26:20.657
- This one won’t.
He’s a good alien.

26:20.704 --> 26:23.334
- You see this?

26:23.373 --> 26:25.753
He did that.

26:25.793 --> 26:28.253
He would kill me
if he had half a chance.

26:28.295 --> 26:32.335
And if it suits him,
that alien will kill you, too.

26:32.382 --> 26:35.092
[dramatic music]

26:35.135 --> 26:39.005
Here, call me when you’re ready
to tell me who he is.

26:39.056 --> 26:42.266
All of humanity
might be at stake.

26:42.309 --> 26:47.359
♪ ♪

26:47.397 --> 26:50.687
- There is a word
for little boys like Max--

26:50.734 --> 26:52.244
"traitor."

26:52.277 --> 26:54.027
[engine turning over]

26:54.071 --> 26:56.871
And also "shit weasel"
and "dink."

26:56.907 --> 26:58.527
There are many words.

27:03.413 --> 27:06.003
- Here you go, honey.
- Mmm, thank you, hon.

27:06.041 --> 27:07.961
- Excellent soup.
- Mm-hmm.

27:08.001 --> 27:09.381
- Oh, thank you.

